Abstract

This document presents a conservatively engineered mathematical and architectural framework for Orbital Compute Nodes (OCNs). It corrects prior over-optimistic assumptions, most critically the radiative heat rejection capacity, and grounds all claims in first-principles physics and recent experimental data (Google Suncatcher, Starcloud). Core contributions include: 1) A corrected radiator model yielding ~1.6 kW/m² sustainable compute density; 2) A pragmatic state-based control architecture justified by orbital periodicity; 3) System performance and reliability bounds derived from conservative component models and fault-tolerance strategies. The resulting OCN-1000 design achieves a defensible 280-350 TFLOPS-hr per orbit within a 5,500 kg mass budget.

