1.2 Radiative Heat Rejection: Corrected First-Principles Model

Theorem 1.1 (Net Radiative Cooling Capacity). For an OCN with radiator area A_r at temperature T_s, the maximum net power P_{net}^{max} that can be rejected is:

P_{net}^{max}(T_s) = \epsilon \sigma A_r T_s^4 - \alpha A_r \Phi_{eff}

where \Phi_{eff} is the effective solar flux incident on the radiator.

Proof. Consider a radiator panel in LEO. The total power balance per unit area is:

P_{out} = \epsilon \sigma T_s^4 \quad \text{(Emitted IR)}

P_{in} = \alpha \Phi_{eff} \quad \text{(Absorbed Solar)}

The net cooling power is P_{net} = P_{out} - P_{in}. For a two-sided radiator (emitting from both sides) with one side illuminated, the total area for emission is 2A_r, but absorption occurs only on one side:

P_{net}^{max} = 2\epsilon \sigma A_r T_s^4 - \alpha A_r \Phi_0

assuming normal incidence during peak insolation. ∎

Corollary 1.1.1 (Sustainable Compute Density). At T_s^{max} = 358 \ \text{K}:

P_{out} = 2 \times 0.92 \times 5.67\times10^{-8} \times (358)^4 \approx 1.72 \times 10^3 \ \text{W/m}^2

P_{in} = 0.10 \times 1361 \approx 136 \ \text{W/m}^2

P_{net}^{max} \approx 1584 \ \text{W/m}^2 \quad \text{(\textbf{1.58 kW/m²})}

This corrects the previous erroneous claim of ~2.0 kW/m². Realistic engineering margins (non-ideal view factors, degradation) suggest using 1.1–1.3 kW/m² for design.

Design Implication: For a target compute power P_c, the required radiator area is:

A_r^{min} = \frac{P_c}{\eta_{net}} \quad \text{with} \ \eta_{net} \in [1.1, 1.6] \ \text{kW/m}^2

