1.3 Orbital Power System Model

Lemma 1.2 (Orbital Energy Harvesting). The average solar power harvested over one orbit is:

\overline{P_{solar}} = \eta_{pv} \eta_{point} A_s \Phi_0 (1 - f_e)

where \eta_{pv} = 0.32 (triple-junction GaAs), \eta_{point} = 0.95 (pointing loss), A_s is array area, and f_e is eclipse fraction.

For 500 km SSO (\beta \approx 0^\circ), f_e \approx 0.35, thus:

\overline{P_{solar}} \approx 0.32 \times 0.95 \times 1361 \times (1-0.35) A_s \approx 269 \ A_s \ \text{W}

Each m² of solar array provides ~269 W average power.

Energy Storage Requirement: To maintain compute power P_c during eclipse duration t_e = f_e T_{orbit}:

E_{batt}^{min} = \frac{P_c \ t_e}{\eta_{discharge} \ DOD_{max}}

With \eta_{discharge} = 0.95, DOD_{max} = 0.8 (for cycle life), t_e = 0.35 \times 5400s = 1890s:

E_{batt}^{min} \approx 1.32 \ P_c \ t_e

