1.4 PCM as Thermal Buffer: Conservative Model

Theorem 1.3 (PCM Mass Requirement). To buffer a compute power excess \Delta P = P_c - \overline{P_{solar}} for duration t_{buffer}, the PCM mass required is:

m_{pcm} = \frac{\Delta P \ t_{buffer}}{L_{eff} \ \eta_{pcm}}

where L_{eff} is effective latent heat and \eta_{pcm} is system efficiency.

Proof. The energy to be stored is E_{store} = \Delta P \ t_{buffer}. PCM storage capacity is m_{pcm} L_{eff} \eta_{pcm}. Equating gives the result. ∎

Conservative Parameters:

· Effective Latent Heat: For paraffin wax in Al encapsulation, L_{eff} \approx 150 \ \text{kJ/kg} (not 200 kJ/kg)
· System Efficiency: \eta_{pcm} \approx 0.75 (accounts for thermal resistance)
· Typical Buffer Time: t_{buffer} \approx 0.3 \times t_{sun} \approx 1050s

Example: For \Delta P = 15 \ \text{kW} (40 kW peak vs 25 kW average solar):

m_{pcm} = \frac{15000 \times 1050}{150000 \times 0.75} \approx 140 \ \text{kg}

Total for margins and distribution: 200–250 kg is prudent.

