1.5 State-Based Control: A Pragmatic Optimization

Problem 1.1 (State Quantization Trade-off). Find the number of orbital states N that minimizes the total loss per orbit:

\mathcal{L}(N) = \underbrace{\frac{T_{orbit}}{2\pi N} \cdot \frac{dP_{opt}}{d\phi}}_{\text{Phase error loss}} + \underbrace{N \cdot C_{trans}}_{\text{Transition cost}}

where C_{trans} is the energy/time cost of changing compute state.

Proof Sketch. Quantizing the orbital phase \phi(t) = 2\pi t/T_{orbit} into N states introduces a phase error \sim T_{orbit}/(2\pi N). The power loss grows with phase error. Each state transition incurs cost C_{trans} (DVFS settling, checkpoint overhead). ∎

Corollary 1.5.1 (Optimal State Count). The optimal N^* satisfies:

\frac{d\mathcal{L}}{dN} = 0 \ \Rightarrow \ N^* = \sqrt{\frac{T_{orbit}}{2\pi C_{trans}} \cdot \frac{dP_{opt}}{d\phi}}

For typical values: T_{orbit}=5400s, C_{trans}=10s (DVFS+checkpoint), dP_{opt}/d\phi \approx 0.5 \ \text{kW/rad}:

N^* \approx \sqrt{\frac{5400 \times 0.5}{2\pi \times 10}} \approx \sqrt{43} \approx 6.6

Engineering Choice: N = 5–7 states captures the optimum. Claiming "94.2% of MPC" is unsupported; instead: "A 5-state controller captures the major orbital phases with minimal control complexity."

